ople who were candidates during previous federal elections -->\n;'''Other prominent individuals:'''\n;'''Organizations:'''\n;'''Media:'''\n}}\n\n===Dimitri Lascaris===\n[[File:DimitriLascaris.jpg|thumb|upright|Dimitri Lascaris]]\n;Background:\nLascaris was the party's candidate for [[London West]] in 2015, former Justice critic in the Green Party's [[shadow cabinet]] (2016), lawyer and activist in Montreal who sits on the Quebec Greens' executive council.<ref name=\"staralex\" />\n:'''Candidacy announced:''' 11 March 2020<ref>{{Citation|title=Campaign Announcement|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IPdRBqki1B4|language=en|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n:'''Date registered with Elections Canada:'''\n:'''Campaign website:''' {{URL|www.TeamDimitri.ca}}\n\n;Policies:\n*institute labour reforms to increase union membership.<ref name=\"lascaris-policy1\">{{cite news |last1=Thurton |first1=David |title=Green Party leadership contender courts 'disgruntled' NDPers |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/lascaris-green-party-leadership-1.5496663 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |publisher=[[CBC News]] |date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n*prevent the user of [[Strikebreaker|replacement workers]] during strikes.<ref name=\"lascaris-policy1\"/>\n*raise the minimum wage.<ref name=\"lascaris-policy1\"/>\n*increase income tax on wealthy Canadians and institute a cap on wealth.<ref name=\"lascaris-policy1\"/>\n*make housing a human right.<ref name=\"lascaris-policy1\"/>\n*dramatically reduce military spending.<ref name=\"lascaris-policy1\"/>\n\n{{Endorsements box\n|df=yes| title = Endorsements of Dimitri Lascaris\n| list =\n;'''MPs:'''\n;'''Provincial politicians:'''\n;'''Municipal politicians:'''\n*Elizabeth Peloza, Councillor, City of [[London, Ontario]].<ref>https://twitter.com/ElizabethPeloza/status/1237804766337564672?s=20</ref>\n;'''Former MPs:'''\n;'''Former provincial politicians:'''\n*[[Don Scott (Manitoba politician)|Don Scott]], Manitoba NDP MLA for [[Inkster (electoral district)|Inkster]] (1981-1988), Green Party of Canada Vice President, 2014\u20142016.<ref>https://twitter.com/DonaldAScott/status/1240018406968967168?s=20</ref>\n;'''Former municipal politicians:'''\n;'''Former candidates:''' \n*[[Joan Russow]], former leader of the Green Party of Canada (1997-2001)<ref>https://www.teamdimitri.ca/campaign_announcement</ref>\n* Richard Walsh, candidate for [[Waterloo (electoral district)|Waterloo]], 2015.<ref>https://twitter.com/RichardTGWalsh/status/1238279365877731329?s=20</ref>\n<!-- These must be people who were candidates during previous federal elections -->\n;'''Other prominent individuals:'''\n;'''Organizations:'''\n;'''Media:'''\n}}\n\n===Alex Tyrrell===\n[[File:AlexTyrrellPVQ.jpg|thumb|upright|Alex Tyrrell]]\n;Background\n[[Alex Tyrrell]], {{age|1988|3|23}}, is the leader of the [[Green Party of Quebec]] (2013\u2013present), and was the provincial candidate for [[Verdun (provincial electoral district)|Verdun]] in 2018 with 80 votes, [[Notre-Dame-de-Gr\u00e2ce (provincial electoral district)|Notre-Dame-de-Gr\u00e2ce]] in 2014, and [[Jacques-Cartier]] in 2012. He was also the candidate in the [[Outremont (provincial electoral district)|Outremont]], [[Chicoutimi (provincial electoral district)|Chicoutimi]], [[Gouin (electoral district)|Gouin]], [[Louis-H\u00e9bert (provincial electoral district)|Louis-H\u00e9bert]], and [[Roberval (provincial electoral district)|Roberval]] by-elections in 2013, 2016, May 2017, October 2017 and 2018, respectively.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/green-party-elizabeth-may-alex-tyrrell-leadership-race-1.5346324|title=Quebec's Green Party leader eyeing federal job if Elizabeth May steps down|publisher=[[CBC News]]|access-date=November 4, 2019}}</ref>\n:'''Candidacy announced:''' 15 January 2020<ref name=\"tyrrellcbc\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/quebec-green-party-leader-to-join-federal-leadership-race-as-an-eco-socialist-candidate-1.5426482|title=Quebec Green Party leader to join federal leadership race as an 'eco-socialist' candidate, attempting to change the direction of the Greens|last=Thurton|first=David|work=CBC News|date=January 14, 2020|accessdate=January 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Laframbroise|first=Kalina|title=Quebec Green Party leader officially launches bid to replace Elizabeth May |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6414594/quebec-alex-tyrrell-green-party-leadership-race/|date=January 15, 2020|accessdate=January 15, 2020|work=Global News}}</ref>\n:'''Date registered with Elections Canada:'''\n:'''Campaign website:''' {{URL|https://www.alextyrrell.ca}}\n\n;Policies:\n*Close Alberta's oilsands within the first four years of a Green mandate.<ref name=\"tyrrellcbc\" />\n*Link major cities in Canada by high-speed electric rail.<ref name=\"tyrrellcbc\" />\n*Generate new revenues and, where necessary, incur deficits to accommodate his green transition and abandon \"fiscal conservatism.\"<ref name=\"tyrrellcbc\" />\n*Amend the Constitution to guarantee Canadians access to clean air, water, housing and healthy food.<ref name=\"tyrrellcbc\" />\n*Is running as an [[eco-socialism|eco-socialist]].<ref>{{cite web|author=M. Bramadat-Willcock |url=https://www.nationalobserver.com/2020/01/14/news/alex-tyrrell-eco-socialist-quebec-green-leader-makes-federal-bid |title=Alex Tyrrell, eco-socialist Quebec Green leader, makes federal bid |publisher=National Observer |date=2020-01-14 |accessdate=2020-02-24}}</ref>\n\n{{Endorsements box\n|df=yes| title = Endorsements of Alex Tyrrell\n| list =\n;'''MPs:'''\n;'''Provincial politicians:'''\n;'''Municipal politicians:'''\n;'''Former MPs:'''\n;'''Former provincial politicians:'''\n;'''Former municipal politicians:'''\n;'''Former candidates:''' <!-- These must be people who were candidates during previous federal elections -->\n;'''Other prominent individuals:'''\n;'''Organizations:'''\n;'''Media:'''\n}}\n\n==Withdrawn==\n\n===Julie Tremblay-Cloutier===\n;Background\nJulie Tremblay-Cloutier, 48, is a businesswoman from [[Oka, Quebec|Oka]] who was the Green Party candidate for [[Mirabel (electoral district)|Mirabel]] in 2019, and a candidate for Oka City Council in 2017. Prior to entering politics, Tremblay-Cloutier was the head of a local pool and spa inspection company,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ballingall |first1=Alex |title=A Quebec businesswoman and disenchanted ex-Liberal enter the race to replace Elizabeth May |url=https://www.thestar.com/politics/federal/2019/12/02/a-quebec-businesswomen-and-disenchanted-ex-liberal-enter-the-race-to-replace-elizabeth-may.html |accessdate=27 January 2020 |publisher=[[Toronto Star]] |date=2 December 2019}}</ref> In a Facebook posting, Tremblay-Cloutier remarked \"You have to know that you have to find $ 10000 / month in donations to be able to keep the road. This activity had become at the centre of the campaign; as ideas and debates became secondary.\"\n\n:'''Candidacy announced:''' 2 December 2019<ref name=\"staralex\">{{cite news |last1=Ballingall |first1=Alex |title=A Quebec businesswomen and disenchanted ex-Liberal enter the race to replace Elizabeth May |url=https://www.thestar.com/politics/federal/2019/12/02/a-quebec-businesswomen-and-disenchanted-ex-liberal-enter-the-race-to-replace-elizabeth-may.html |accessdate=December 2, 2019 |work=Toronto Star |date=December 2, 2019}}</ref>\n:'''Withdrew:''' 14 February 2020<ref name=\"Facebook\">{{cite news |title=Facebook |url=https://www.facebook.com/julietremblaycloutierpvc/posts/3471004506274934?hc_location=ufi&comment_id=Y29tbWVudDoyNTg1NTk2MDc4MzI2MzYwXzI1ODU2Mjk3ODgzMjI5ODk%3D |accessdate=March 8, 2020 |work=Facebook |date=February 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Constantine Kritsonis===\n;Background:\nConstantine Kritsonis, {{age|1957|3|22}}, is a former Ontario representative on the Green Party Council. He stood as the Green Party of Canada candidate for [[York Centre]] in 2015, 2011, 2006, 2004 and 1997, and the [[Green Party of Ontario]] candidate in [[Oakwood (provincial electoral district)|Oakwood]] in 1995.<ref>{{cite web |title=Federal Council - Ontario - Constantine Kritsonis |url=https://www.greenparty.ca/en/content/federal-council-ontario-constantine-kritsonis |website=Green Party of Canada |accessdate=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n:'''Candidacy announced:''' 23 January 2020<ref name=\"green-kritsonis\"/>\n:'''Withdrew:''' 3 February 2020<ref name=\"withdraw\">{{cite news |title=Green party\u2019s leadership race rules, entry fee has some candidates balking |url=https://www.thestar.com/politics/federal/2020/02/03/green-party-sets-contest-rules-to-elect-new-leader-in-october.html |accessdate=February 3, 2020 |work=Toronto Star |date=February 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n;Policies:\n* End government subsidies of corporations.<ref name=\"green-kritsonis\"/>\n\n==Expressed interest==\n*Luc Joli-Coeur, candidate for [[Qu\u00e9bec (electoral district)|Qu\u00e9bec]] in 2019, government manager for the Quebec Department of Finance and former political advisor under the Marois and Parizeau governments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lesoleil.com/actualite/politique/luc-joli-cur-interesse-par-la-direction-du-parti-vert-du-canada-38c59b1d02b1fa22277086ebb3a4583e|title=Luc Joli-C\u0153ur int\u00e9ress\u00e9 par la direction du Parti vert du Canada|date=November 5, 2019|website=Le Soleil|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|quote=Luc Joli-C\u0153ur interested in the leadership of the Green Party of Canada}}</ref>\n\n==Declined==\n*[[Jenica Atwin]], MP for [[Fredericton (electoral district)|Fredericton]] (2019\u2013present)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straight.com/news/1321481/elizabeth-may-resigns-leader-green-party-canada-will-remain-partys-parliamentary-leader|title=Elizabeth May resigns as leader of the Green Party of Canada but will remain as party's parliamentary leader|date=November 4, 2019|website=The Georgia Straight|access-date=November 4, 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Peter Bevan-Baker]], [[Leader of the Opposition (Prince Edward Island)