 = [[File:Candidate-amita-kuttner.jpg|150x150px]]\n| image1_size       = 180x180px\n| colour1           = 9966CC\n| 1blank            = Riding\n| 1data1            = N/A{{efn|Resident of British Columbia. Ran in [[Burnaby North\u2014Seymour]] in 2019}}\n<!--David Merner-->\n| candidate2        = [[#David Merner|David Merner]]\n| image2            = [[File:David Merner 2012.jpg|150x150px]]\n| image2_size       = 180x180px\n| colour2           = DC143C\n| 2blank            = Riding\n| 1data2            = N/A{{efn|Resident of British Columbia. Ran in [[Esquimalt\u2014Saanich\u2014Sooke]] in 2019}}\n<!--Annamie Paul-->\n| candidate3        = {{nowrap|[[#Annamie Paul|Annamie Paul]]}}\n| image3            = [[File:Annamie Paul in Toronto Regent Park.jpg|150x150px]]\n| image3_size       = 180x180px\n| colour3           = EFCC00\n| 3blank            = Riding\n| 1data3            = N/A{{efn|Resident of Ontario. Ran in [[Toronto Centre]] in 2019}}\n\n| map_image         = Canada Federal Ridings Map.svg\n| map_caption       = Map of Canada by constituency\n}}\n\n{{Infobox Canadian leadership election\n| colour      = {{Canadian party colour|CA|Green}}\n| party       = Green Party \n| year = 2020\n| logo = \n| date = October 4, 2020\n| location = [[Charlottetown]], [[Prince Edward Island]]\n| replaces    = [[Elizabeth May]]\n| winner     = TBD\n| ballots = \n| numcands = \n| entryfee = $50,000<ref name=\"Rules\">{{cite news |title=Green party sets contest rules to elect new leader in October |url=https://www.thestar.com/politics/federal/2020/02/03/green-party-sets-contest-rules-to-elect-new-leader-in-october.html |accessdate=February 3, 2020 |work=Toronto Star |agency=Canadian Press |date=February 3, 2020}}</ref>\n| spendcap = $500,000<ref name=\"Rules\"/>\n}}\nThe 2020 '''[[Green Party of Canada]] [[Green Party of Canada leadership elections|leadership election]]''' will take place on October 4, 2020 to elect a leader to replace [[Elizabeth May]], who resigned on November 4, 2019<ref name=\"leadership date\"/><ref name=\"CTV2019\">{{cite news |last1=Aiello |first1=Rachel |title=Elizabeth May steps down as Green Party leader {{!}} CTV News |url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/elizabeth-may-steps-down-as-green-party-leader-1.4669169 |accessdate=November 4, 2019 |work=ctvnews.ca |publisher=CTV News |date=November 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6124129/elizabeth-may-resigns-green-party/|title=Elizabeth May steps down as leader of Green Party|website=Global News|access-date=November 4, 2019}}</ref>  after leading the party for more than a decade and achieving a record three seats in [[House of Commons of Canada|Parliament]] in the [[Canadian federal election, 2019|2019 federal election]].\n\n==Timeline==\n\n*October 24, 2019 - Elizabeth May announced that she would step down as leader within the next four years, but intended to continue for \"the near term\", as an early election could complicate the transition.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/green-party-priorities-letter-trudeau-1.5333869|title=Elizabeth May says she's staying on as leader \u2014 for now|last=May|first=Elizabeth|date=October 24, 2019|publisher=CBC News|access-date=November 7, 2019}}</ref> \n*November 3, 2019 - a group of party members launched a petition calling for an open leadership race to ensure the \"long-term prosperity of the party\"; among those members was [[Green Party of Quebec]] leader [[Alex Tyrrell]], who expressed interest in running.<ref>{{cite news |title=Quebec's Green Party leader eyeing federal job if Elizabeth May steps down |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/green-party-elizabeth-may-alex-tyrrell-leadership-race-1.5346324 |accessdate=23 November 2019 |publisher=[[CBC News]] |date=3 November 2019}}</ref> \n*November 4, 2019 -  May announced she was stepping down as leader effective immediately. [[Jo-Ann Roberts]] was named [[interim leader]]. May stayed on as the parliamentary leader in the House.<ref name=\"CTV2019\"/> \n*February 3, 2020 - The rules for the leadership race were released. A total of $50,000 in fees is required from each candidate. This amount was criticized by several potential candidates, causing some to decide against running.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/green-party-s-leadership-race-rules-entry-fee-has-some-candidates-balking-1.4795180|title=Green party's leadership race rules, entry fee has some candidates balking|last=Rabson|first=Mia|date=February 3, 2020|work=CTV News|access-date=February 6, 2020}}</ref>\n*February 4, 2020 - Nomination period opens<ref name=\"rules\">https://www.greenparty.ca/sites/default/files/2020_gpc_leadership_contest_rules.pdf</ref>\n*March 24, 2020 - The candidacy of Annamie Paul is approved.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*April 4, 2020 - The candidacy of David Merner is approved.<ref name=\":1\" />\n*April 22, 2020 - The candidacy of Amita Kuttner is approved.<ref name=\"gree_Amit\" />\n*June 3, 2020, 6 pm PDT - Nomination period closes.<ref name=\"rules\"/>\n*July 31, 2020 - Deadline for receipt of secondary non-refundable fee of $40,000 (in addition to $1,000 at time of filing application to run and $9,000 ten days after application received).<ref name=\"rules\"/>\n*August 1 - September 1, 2020 - Leadership candidates must supply signatures of 150 party members, at least 20 of which must be from each of six regions. Signatures are in addition to 100 signatures provided with leadership application.<ref name=\"rules\"/>\n*September 3, 2020, 11:59 PM PDT - deadline to become a member of the Green Party and be eligible to vote.<ref name=\"rules\"/>\n*September 25, 2020 - deadline for receipt of mail-in ballots.<ref name=\"rules\"/>\n*September 26, 2020 - online voting begins.<ref name=\"rules\"/>\n*October 3, 2020-\n**3:30 PM PDT - online voting ends.<ref name=\"rules\"/>\n**5 PM PDT - results announced.<ref name=\"rules\"/>\n\n==Approved candidates==\n\n===Amita Kuttner===\n;Background:\n[[File:Candidate-amita-kuttner.jpg|thumb|upright|Amita Kuttner]]\nAmita Kuttner is an astrophysicist from [[North Vancouver (city)|North Vancouver]], currently living on [[Lasqueti Island]].<ref name=\"KuttnerElxn19\">{{cite news |last1=Richter |first1=Brent |title=Astrophysicist Amita Kuttner runs for Greens in Burnaby North-Seymour |url=https://www.nsnews.com/news/astrophysicist-amita-kuttner-runs-for-greens-in-burnaby-north-seymour-1.23826827 |accessdate=9 March 2020 |publisher=[[North Shore News]] |date=18 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"amit_Bio\u2013\">{{Cite web |title=Bio \u2013 Amita Kuttner |author=Amita Kuttner |work=amitakuttner.ca |date=10 March 2020 |access-date=10 March 2020 |url= https://amitakuttner.ca/bio/ }}</ref> They<!--Please do not change pronouns without discussing on talk page.--> formerly served as the Green Party's Science and Innovation Critic.<ref name=\"gree_Shad\">{{Cite web |title=Shadow Cabinet |work=Green Party of Canada |access-date=9 March 2020 |url= https://www.greenparty.ca/en/party/structure/cabinet }}</ref><ref name=\"KuttnerAnnounce\" />  During the 2019 federal election, Kuttner was the party's candidate for [[Burnaby North\u2014Seymour]].<ref name=\"KuttnerElxn19\" /> They<!--Please do not change pronouns without discussing on talk page.--> are openly [[Non-binary gender|non-binary]] and [[Pansexuality|pansexual]], and use [[Singular they|''they/them'' pronouns]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hyslop |first1=Katie |title=Amita Kuttner on Being a Green, Non-Binary, and Pansexual Astrophysicist and Politician |url=https://thetyee.ca/News/2019/08/26/Amita-Kuttner-Green-Candidate |accessdate=9 March 2020 |publisher=[[The Tyee]] |date=26 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Godfrey |first1=Dustin |title=North Shore Green candidate enters federal party\u2019s leadership race |url=https://www.nsnews.com/news/north-shore-green-candidate-enters-federal-party-s-leadership-race-1.24094002 |accessdate=9 March 2020 |publisher=[[North Shore News]] |date=9 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Gawley |first1=Kelvin |title=\u2018I was freaking out\u2019: Burnaby Green candidate comes out as non-binary |url=https://www.burnabynow.com/news/i-was-freaking-out-burnaby-green-candidate-comes-out-as-non-binary-1.23908762 |accessdate=9 March 2020 |publisher=[[Burnaby Now]] |date=7 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n:'''Candidacy announced:''' 9 March 2020<ref name=\"KuttnerAnnounce\">{{cite news |last1=MacLeod |first1=Andrew |title=New Candidate for Green Leadership Has Known Environmental Catastrophe |url=https://thetyee.ca/News/2020/03/09/New-Candidate-Green-Leadership |accessdate=9 March 2020 |publisher=[[The Tyee]] |date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n:'''Candidacy approved:''' 22 April 2020<ref name=\"gree_Amit\">{{Cite web |title=Amita Kuttner is a contestant for Green Party of Canada leadership |date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020 |url= https://www.greenparty.ca/en/media-release/2020-04-22/amita-kuttner-contestant-green-party-canada-leadership }}</ref>\n\n:'''Date registered with Elections Canada:''' \n:'''Campaign website:''' https://amitakuttner.ca\n\n;Policies:\n\n{{Endorsements box\n|df=yes| title = Endorsements of Amita Kuttner\n| list =\n;'''MPs:'''\n;'''Provincial politicians:'''\n*[[Sonia Furstenau]] (British Columbia MLA for [[Cowichan Valley (provincial electoral district)|Cowichan Valley]] and candidate in the [[2020 Green Party of British Columbia leadership election]])<ref name=\"furstenau\">{{cite news |last1=Gawley |first1=Kevin |title=Non-binary astrophysicist joins Green Party of Canada leadership race |url=https://www.citynews1130.com/2020/03/09/non-binary-astrophysicist-joins-green-party-of-canada-leadership-race/ |accessdate=12 March 2020 |publisher=News 1130 |date=9 March 2020 |quote=Furstenau\u2019s leadership co-campaign manager said the MLA was \u201cproviding a soft endorsement of Amita\u2019s candidacy and is also supportive of Annamie Paul\u2019s candidacy.\"}}</ref>\n;'''Municipal politicians:''' \n*David Demers (Vancouver Park Board Commissioner)<ref name=\"Amitannounce\">{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/watch/?v=205539894141679 |title=This morning I announced that I am running to be Leader of the Green Party of Canada! |last=Kuttner |first=Amita |date=9 March 2020 |website=Facebook |publisher=Amita Kuttner |access-date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Pete Fry]] (Vancouver City Councillor)<ref name=\"Amitannounce\" /> \n*Megan Curren (District of North Vancouver Councillor)<ref name=\"Amitannounce\" />\n;'''Former MPs:'''\n;'''Former provincial politicians:'''\n;'''Former municipal politicians:'''\n;'''Former candidates:''' \n*Bridget Burns (2019 Green Party candidate for Vancouver East)<ref name=\"Amitannounce\" />\n*George Orr (2019 Green Party candidate for North Vancouver)<ref name=\"Amitannounce\" /> <!-- These must be people who were candidates during previous federal elections -->\n;'''Other prominent individuals:''' \n*Anthony Hughes (Chairperson of the [[Green Party of Vancouver]])<ref name=\"Amitannounce\" />\n*Nicola Spurling (Tri-Cities Pride Society President, Vancouver Pride Society Outreach Chair, and Lower Mainland Representative to the BC Greens Provincial Council)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/NicESpurling/posts/813967539014142 |title=Nicola Spurling - Post |last=Spurling |first=Nicola |date=9 March 2020 |website=Facebook |publisher=Nicola Spurling |access-date=9 March 2020 |quote=I\u2019ve had the pleasure of working on Amita Kuttner\u2019s campaign and know first hand how incredible they are. Their work ethic, their commitment to principled and evidence-based decision making, and their care for people and the environment is unparalleled. I also feel strongly that we need better representation and more progressive ideas within the federal Green Party and politics in Canada as a whole. As an LGBTQ2+ person of colour, Amita brings much-needed representation and I know their views to be progressive, thoughtful and based on science, facts and research. I wholeheartedly endorse Amita Kuttner in their bid to be leader of the Green Party of Canada. }}</ref> \n;'''Organizations:'''\n;'''Media:'''\n}}\n\n===David Merner===\n[[File:David Merner 2012.jpg|thumb|upright|David Merner]]\n;Background:\nDavid Merner, 57, is the Green Party Critic for Justice (2018-present), and was the Green Party candidate for [[Esquimalt\u2014Saanich\u2014Sooke]] in 2019. From 2012 to 2013, he was the president of the [[Liberal Party of Canada]]'s [[British Columbia]] wing and was their candidate for [[Esquimalt\u2014Saanich\u2014Sooke]] in 2015. Prior to entering politics, Merner was a lawyer at the [[Department of Justice (Canada)|Department of Justice]] and for the [[Privy Council Office (Canada)]] as well as the Ministry of [[Attorney General of British Columbia]].\n:'''Candidacy announced:''' 5 November 2019<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hilltimes.com/2019/11/06/leadership-contest-could-see-2020-greens-surpass-ndp-in-fundraising-says-contender/223665|title=Leadership contest could see 2020 Greens surpass NDP in fundraising, says contender|last=Times|first=The Hill|date=November 6, 2019|website=The Hill Times|access-date=November 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/palakmangat/status/1192637647090573317|title=Little bit of #cdnpoli news here: ex-Liberal David Merner, who ran under Green banner in #elxn43 in his BC riding, is vying to replace former Green leader Elizabeth May|last=Mangat|first=Palak|date=November 7, 2019|website=Twitter|access-date=November 12, 2019}}</ref>\n:'''Candidacy approved:''' 8 April 2020<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.greenparty.ca/en/media-release/2020-04-08/david-merner-contestant-green-party-canada-leadership|title=David Merner is a contestant for Green Party of Canada leadership|date=April 8, 2020|access-date=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n:'''Date registered with Elections Canada:'''\n:'''Campaign website:''' {{URL|https://www.davidmerner.com/}}\n